Introduction to R: Week 4 Solutions

FACS example

Maria Doyle

21 May 2019

Youve run a FACS experiment and you need to calculate percentages of the cell types youve measured and visualise the data. You can do it in Excel but its becoming very tedious and error-prone because you have several experiments you need to analyse.

Lets try to use what weve learnt about R and the tidyverse to analyse and visualise the data.

  • Read in the Excel file called facs_example_data.xlsx, save it as an object called facs. Hint: use library(readxl) and Google to find the function
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
facs <- read_excel("/training/r-intro-tidyverse/data/facs_example_data.xlsx")

-
/
  • How many rows and columns are in the file?

There should be 21 rows and 9 columns

  • Remove the rows containing the test Samples (Test-1, Test-2 and Test-3). Hint: use filter and !str_detect (! means not)
facs <- filter(facs, !str_detect(Sample, "Test"))
  • Add a column called CD4T_percent that contains the CD4T column value as a percent of the T_Cells column for each sample
facs <- mutate(facs, CD4T_percent = CD4T / T_Cells * 100)
  • Add more columns with the Column Name below containing values that are calculations of cell percentages from the named columns e.g.CD8T_percent is the CD8T column as a percent of the T_Cells column.

Column Name Value CD8T_percent CD8T as percent of T_Cells Treg_percent Treg as percent of CD4T Th_percent Th as percent of CD4T B_percent B as percent of CD45.1 NK_percent NK as percent of CD45.1

facs <- mutate(facs,
                   CD8T_percent = CD8T / T_Cells * 100,
                   Treg_percent = Treg / CD4T * 100,
                   Th_percent = Th / CD4T * 100,
                   B_percent = B / CD45.1 * 100,
                   NK_percent = NK / CD45.1 * 100)
  • Add a column called Group containing a value for whether the Sample is Isotype, PBS or Treatment. Hint: use case_when and str_detect
facs <- mutate(facs, Group=case_when(
  str_detect(Sample, "PBS")  ~ "PBS",
  str_detect(Sample, "Isotype")  ~ "Isotype",
  str_detect(Sample, "Treatment")  ~ "Treatment"
))
  • Make jitter plots of the values for the groups. Hints:
  1. First convert values to long format with gather, call the key column Cell and the value column Value.
  2. Then make jitter plots with Group on the x axis and Value on the y axis.
  3. Facet by the Cell column to get plots for each cell percentage
facs <- gather(facs, key=Cell, value=Value, ends_with("_percent")) 
ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group, y=Value)) +
  geom_jitter()

ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group, y=Value)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell)

  • Colour by sample. Bonus if you use colour-blind friendly colours. Hint: Google
ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group, y=Value, colour=Sample)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell)

  • Change the plot to colour the groups.
ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group, y=Value, colour=Group)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell)

  • Order the groups along the x axis (and legend) as PBS, Isotype, Treatment. Hint: use factor and levels
group_order <-  c("PBS", "Isotype", "Treatment")
facs <- mutate(facs, Group_f=factor(Group, levels=group_order))
  • Order the jitter plots as CD4T_percent, CD8T_percent, Treg_percent, Th_percent, NK_percent, B_percent. Hint: use factor and levels
cell_order <-  c("CD4T_percent", "CD8T_percent", "Treg_percent", "Th_percent", "NK_percent", "B_percent")
facs <- mutate(facs, Cell_f=factor(Cell, levels=cell_order))
ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group_f, y=Value, colour=Group_f)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell_f)

Note: saving from here on as p to make easier to see the line they need to add

p <- ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group_f, y=Value, colour=Group_f)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell)
p

  • Change the X axis label to Condition
p <- p + labs(x="Condition")
p

  • Change the Y axis label to Percentage
p <- p + labs(y="Percentage")
p

  • Remove the grey background. Use any theme e.g.theme_bw or theme_minimal
p <- p + theme_bw()
p

  • Make the x axis labels vertical
p <- p + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))
p

  • Remove the legend title (we didnt cover this theyll need to Google)
p <- p + theme(legend.title=element_blank())
p

p <- p + theme(legend.title=element_blank())
p

  • Add a title called My FACS plots
p <- p + labs(title="My FACS plot")
p

  • Centre the title
p <- p + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
p

  • Save the plot as a PDF called facs_plot.pdf
pdf("facs_plot.pdf")
p
dev.off()

  • Save the table used to make the plot as a file (i.e.containing the % columns) as a tab-separated file called facs_analysis.tsv. Hint: see the write_tsv function.
write_tsv(facs, "facs_analysis.tsv")
  • Read in the FACS file from an second experiment that uses the same markers and number of samples. Make a pdf of plots similer to the first experiment. Save it as facs_plot_expt2.pdf.

They should be able to run the code theyve already written with minimal changes, just change the name of the file theyve read in and the output pdf name. This is to show how easy it can be to reuse code once its been written. The entire code for this is below.

facs <- read_excel("/training/r-intro-tidyverse/data/facs_example_data2.xlsx")

-
/
                                                                                                                                        
facs <- filter(facs, !str_detect(Sample, "Test"))
facs <- mutate(facs, CD4T_percent = CD4T / T_Cells * 100)
facs <- mutate(facs,
                   CD8T_percent = CD8T / T_Cells * 100,
                   Treg_percent = Treg / CD4T * 100,
                   Th_percent = Th / CD4T * 100,
                   B_percent = B / CD45.1 * 100,
                   NK_percent = NK / CD45.1 * 100)
facs <- mutate(facs, Group=case_when(
  str_detect(Sample, "PBS")  ~ "PBS",
  str_detect(Sample, "Isotype")  ~ "Isotype",
  str_detect(Sample, "Treatment")  ~ "Treatment"
))
facs <- gather(facs, key=Cell, value=Value, ends_with("_percent"))
group_order <-  c("PBS", "Isotype", "Treatment")
facs <- mutate(facs, Group_f=factor(Group, levels=group_order))
cell_order <-  c("CD4T_percent", "CD8T_percent", "Treg_percent", "Th_percent", "NK_percent", "B_percent")
facs <- mutate(facs, Cell_f=factor(Cell, levels=cell_order))
pdf("facs_plot_expt2.pdf")
ggplot(facs, aes(x=Group_f, y=Value, colour=Group_f)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  facet_wrap(~Cell_f) + 
  labs(x="Condition") +
  labs(y="Percentage") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  theme(legend.title=element_blank()) +
  labs(title="My FACS plot") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
dev.off()
